oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:description:
Yesterday I edited the process component's release plan. My experience was less than satisfactory.

Here are the some of the issues I encountered:
- in a bullet point deleting the first characters with the backspace key makes my caret disappear and unpredictable jump to the start or the end of the document
- in other delete cases within a bullet point, the caret jumped to the end of the same line giving my round-robin deletes
- in many cases, decreasing the indent level of a bullet point and its children just did not work, I could increase but to decrease, changing the paragraph type did not help
- pasting a bullet point that has children into a paragraph other than 'Normal, No bullet' is unpredictable, sometimes I got something useful, in most cases rewriting the bullet points was quicker than trying to get the structure right after a paste
- using the 'done' and in 'progress' icons makes all of the previous listed issues with bullet points even more complicated as the icons are sometimes consider as characters, sometimes ignore, but almost always not the way I would have predicted the second before I hit the key
- sometimes the backspace key just stops working - the caret is there - I have to move the caret with the arrow keys to the left and then hit Delete
- when pasting words that are colored, the color sometimes is preserved and sometimes lost but again almost always not as I was guessing
- sometimes when selecting a bullet point be clicking on the bullet I can not change the color, I have to make a textual selection
- selecting lines with shift + arrow keys never selected what I was expecting
- sometimes the caret is invisible, and I haven't found a reliable way yet to bring it back other than closing and reopening the editor, it's there you can set it and type and the charaters are added at the right location
- sometimes when editing an indented bullet pressing enter cause to create a new sibling (expected) and increases the line spacing of all of its siblings and parents (unexpected)
- Find dialog is modal, which makes it useless for quickly navigating around in a larger document and there is no outline that would help with navigation.

Overall, that slowed my down so much that I conducted the following experiment: I converted the text to normal ascii text and applied the edits I wanted to make with the eclipse text editor. This editor is simple and not well suited for bullet lists. As the editor does not support colors, I used textual annotations to express the same information. I was done after 6 minutes compared to more than 2 hours with the planning editor. (Add 2 more minutes to the 6 that it would have taken to apply the color coding.)
oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:title: Editing a plan rich text page is painful

oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:description:
Don noticed that BuildQueryByState was occasionally failing for getting pending builds.  We think this is is because the method getPendingBuilds() first fetches IBuildRequests and then fetches the IBuildResults for those requests.  It can happen that the build is determined to be not necessary and the IBuildResult is deleted on the repo between the time we fetch the request and the result.

This leads to null elements in the array of IBuildResults returned from getPendingBuilds(), which leads to the validation check exception in the call stack.
oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:title: BuildQueryByState for state=NotStarted fails when IBuildResult has been deleted during the query
JzProvider.doFind(resource-list) should add exceptions to the output list, not abort the doFind

oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:description: Each project area must enumerate a global list of choices so that defect reporters can indicate which version a defect was discovered.  The list shouldn't be global per project area, nor should it be necessary in general.  The choices could instead be calculated based on the development lines associated with the owning team area.  Schedule "phases" could be marked private or tagged somehow to prevent them from appearing as a choice.
oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:title: Project Area "static versions" section should be derived instead of explicitly duplicated

oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:description:
We found a bug in the SCM server code where were assuming that a WorkspaceHandle was not a Workspace when it came across the wire. 

While debugging, it seems that this check returned the WorkspaceImpl when checking it against an IWorkspaceHandle

        // if parameter type isn't a handle, just return it.
        if(  ! ITEM_HANDLE_CLASS.isAssignableFrom(parameterType))
            return parameter;

not been read.

oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:title: Read status of news items

oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:description:
The work items view should support configurable and contributable presentations like the work item editor/query editor do. This is tracked in task 23558 and planned for 1.1.

One part of this overall task is to explore and implement a presentation label provider infrastructure that enables clients to write their own presentations quite easily even if the task involves custom draw.

Task:

a) Support simple HTML-like markup to render bold, italic, colors, links. Eclipse 3.4 has support for this, at least to some extent.
b) Allow reuse of the Quick Information presentations (or vice versa). In many cases, they may be the same, and clients shouldn't be forced to contribute to two presentation mechanisms if one can be the default of the other.
c) Allow plain custom draw, but check where we can help implementors with possible intricacies
d) Support an iTunes-like in-cell icon that may represent a link or better affordance for cell editing features (currently, the context menu is column-sensitive, which is hard to discover). This issue is orthogonal to the presentations but also involves custom draw.

Based on the above, implement presentations for
1) Approvals (see work item 49060, a use case for plain custom draw c))
2) Subscriptions (as a use case for a) and b))
3) Links/Attachments (also as a use case for a) and b))
4) Score (a use case for c))

The contribution mechanism itself is not part of this task (this is task 23558)


Some code pointers:

- OwnerDrawLabelProvider
- The richer label support in 3.4
- AbstractQuickInformationEntry
- AttributeLabelProviderFactory (the current label providers for the work items view -- hook your implementations in there to test them)

I have also attached the OwnerDrawLabelProvider that I used in the Twitter exploration. Maybe it is helpful as a starting point.
oslc_cm:ChangeRequest.dc:subject: 3.0_item
